  <exercisegroup>
<introduction>
<p>
In each exercise, determine whether the given subset <m>S</m> of the vector space <m>V</m> is linearly independent. Justify your answer.
</p>
</introduction>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      <m>V=\R^4</m>, <m>S=\{(3,8,7,-3), (1,5,3,-1), (2,-1,2,6), (4,2,6,4)\}</m>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
<exercise>
  <p>
    <m>V=M_{22}</m>, <m>S=\left\{\begin{amatrix}[rr]1\amp 1\\1\amp -3\end{amatrix},
      \begin{amatrix}[rr]1\amp -1\\1\amp -1\end{amatrix},
      \begin{amatrix}[rr]2\amp 1 \\-1\amp -2\end{amatrix},
      \begin{amatrix}[rr]0\amp 1\\1\amp -2\end{amatrix}   \right\}</m>
  </p>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>V=M_{22}</m> and let <m>S=\{ A_1, A_2, A_3\}</m>, where
      <me>
        A_1=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 0\\ 1\amp c \end{bmatrix},  A_2=\begin{bmatrix}-1\amp 0\\ c\amp 1 \end{bmatrix},  A_3=\begin{bmatrix}2\amp 0\\ 1\amp 3 \end{bmatrix}
      </me>.
      Determine all values <m>c\in \R</m> for which <m>S</m> is linearly independent.
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>V=M_{22}</m>,
      and define <m>A_1=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 1\\1\amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>,
      <m>A_2=\begin{bmatrix}0\amp 1\\1\amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>,
      <m>A_3=\begin{bmatrix}1\amp 1\\ 1\amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Compute <m>W=\Span(\{A_1,A_2,A_3\})</m>,
          identifying it as a certain <em>familiar</em> set of matrices.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Decide whether <m>S=\{A_1,A_2,A_3\}</m> is independent.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="ex_linear_independence_arbitrary">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>V</m> be a vector space, and let <m>S=\{\boldv_1, \boldv_2, \dots, \boldv_n\}</m> be a subset of distinct vectors. Assume <m>S</m> is linearly independent. Show that any subset <m>T\subseteq S</m> is linearly independent.
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="ex_span_independence_inveribility">
  <title>Span, independence, and invertibility</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      In this exercise we identify elements of <m>V=\R^n</m> with <m>n\times 1</m> column vectors.
    </p>
    <p> Let <m>S=\{\boldv_1,\boldv_2,\dots, \boldv_n\}</m> be a subset of <m>\R^n</m>, and let <m>A</m> be the <m>n\times n</m> matrix whose <m>j</m>-th column is <m>\boldv_j</m>: <ie />,
      <me>
      A=\begin{bmatrix}\vert \amp \vert \amp \cdots \amp \vert\\ \boldv_1\amp \boldv_2\amp  \amp \boldv_n\\ \vert \amp \vert \amp \cdots \amp \vert \end{bmatrix}
      </me>.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Prove: <m>\Span S=\R^n</m> if and only if <m>A</m> is invertible.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Prove: <m>S</m> is linearly independent if and only if <m>A</m> is invertible.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Use the column method (<xref ref="th_column_method"/>) and the invertibility theorem (<xref ref="th_invertibility_expanded"/>)
    </p>
  </hint>
</exercise>

